The '''''Petropavlovsk'' class''', sometimes referred to as the ''Poltava'' class, was a [[ship class|class]] of three [[pre-dreadnought battleship]]s built for the [[Imperial Russian Navy]] during the 1890s. They were transferred to the [[Russian Pacific Fleet|Pacific Squadron]] upon completion and based at [[Lüshunkou District|Port Arthur]] before the start of the [[Russo-Japanese War]] of 1904–1905. All three ships participated in the [[Battle of Port Arthur]] on the second day of the war. {{ship|Russian battleship|Petropavlovsk|1894|2}} sank two months after the war began after striking one or more [[naval mine|mines]] laid by the Japanese. The remaining two ships participated in the [[Battle of the Yellow Sea]] in August 1904 and were sunk or [[scuttled]] during the final stages of the [[Siege of Port Arthur]].

{{ship|Russian battleship|Poltava|1894|2}} was [[marine salvage|salvaged]] after the Japanese captured Port Arthur and incorporated into the [[Imperial Japanese Navy]]. The ship, renamed ''Tango'' in Japanese service, participated in the [[Battle of Tsingtao]] in late 1914, during [[World War I]]. She was sold back to the Russians in 1916 and renamed ''Chesma'' as her original name was in use by another battleship. The ship became the [[flagship]] of the Russian Arctic Flotilla in 1917 and her crew supported the [[Bolshevik]]s later that year. She was seized by the British in early 1918 when they [[Allied intervention in the Russian Civil War|intervened]] in the [[Russian Civil War]], abandoned by them when they withdrew and [[ship breaking|scrapped]] by the Soviets in 1924.

== Design and description ==
[[File:Poltava correct Brasseys1902.png|thumb|left|250px|Corrected right elevation and deck plan as depicted in [[Brassey's Naval Annual]] 1902]]
Design work for the ''Petropavlovsk'' class began as an enlarged and improved version of the battleship {{ship|Russian battleship|Imperator Nikolai I||2}}, but with her main armament of four {{convert|12|in|0|adj=on}} guns mounted in [[barbettes]]. Based on experience with {{ship|Russian battleship|Imperator Aleksandr II||2}} in which the [[casemate]]-mounted [[Battleship secondary armament|secondary armament]] could often not be worked in rough weather, the Naval Technical Committee adopted the layout of the American {{sclass-|Indiana|battleship|2}}s with the secondary armament of {{convert|8|in|adj=on|0}} guns mounted in [[turret]]s on the upper deck. Use of the lighter barbette mounting allowed for a [[flush deck|flush-deck]] hull which gave the ship high [[Freeboard (nautical)|freeboard]]. The class was designed with a displacement of {{convert|10960|LT|t|0|abbr=on}}, a full-length [[waterline]] [[Belt armor|armor belt]], and the upper hull featured a modest amount of [[tumblehome]]. It was approved in January 1891.{{sfn|McLaughlin|p=85}}

The design was intended to have a maximum speed of {{convert|17|kn|lk=in}} using [[boiler (steam generator)|forced draft]], but model testing of the hull showed that it could only reach {{convert|16|kn}}. Rather than delay construction by redesigning the hull to reach the desired speed, the navy accepted the slower speed. Development of the [[quick-firing gun]] meant that an upper belt of armor was necessary and the weight required was gained by shortening the waterline armor belt, which left the ships' ends protected only by the sloping armor [[deck (ship)|deck]]. Other changes included the replacement of the barbettes with turrets of the same type as used in the battleship {{ship|Russian battleship|Sissoi Veliky||2}} and the substitution of {{convert|6|in|adj=on|0}} quick-firing guns for the original eight-inch guns. This saved enough weight that four additional six-inch guns could be added.{{sfn|McLaughlin|pp=85–86}}

The ''Petropavlovsk''-class ships were {{convert|376|ft|m|1}} [[length overall|long overall]], had a [[Beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|70|ft|m}} and a [[Draft (hull)|draft]] of {{convert|28|ft|3|in|m|1}}. Designed to displace {{convert|10960|LT|t|lk=in}}, they were {{convert|400|-|800|LT|t}} overweight and actually displaced {{convert|11354|-|11842|LT|t}}. The ships were the first [[Flush deck|flush-decked]] battleships built for the Navy. They had a partial [[double bottom]] and the hull was divided by 10 watertight transverse [[bulkhead (partition)|bulkhead]]s; a centerline bulkhead divided the machinery spaces. The upper part of the hull between the main and upper decks curved inwards ([[tumblehome]]), although the tumblehome on these ships was much less pronounced than that found on French battleships of the time, which began curving inwards at the [[waterline]]. They had a designed [[metacentric height]] of {{convert|5.43|ft|m|1}} and were good seagoing ships. Their crew consisted of 26–27 officers and 605–25 enlisted men; ''Petropavlovsk'' had a crew of 750 when serving as a flagship.{{sfn|McLaughlin|pp=84–87}}

The ships were powered by two [[Marine steam engine#Triple or multiple expansion|vertical triple-expansion steam engines]], each driving one propeller, using steam generated by 14 cylindrical [[boiler (steam generator)|boilers]] at a working pressure of {{convert|8.8|atm|kPa psi|0|abbr=on|lk=on}}. Unlike her [[sister ship|sisters]], ''Sevastopol'' had 16 boilers. The engines were rated at {{convert|10600|ihp|lk=in}} and designed to reach a top speed of 16 knots. The machinery for ''Poltava'' and ''Petropavlovsk'' was ordered from British companies and slightly exceeded their specifications; the ships reached maximum speed of {{convert|16.29|and|16.38|kn}} from {{convert|11213|and|11255|ihp}}, respectively, during their [[sea trial]]s. ''Sevastopol'', using domestically built machinery, only reached a speed of {{convert|15.3|kn}} from {{convert|9368|ihp}}, despite the extra boilers, but the Naval Ministry chose not to exercise the penalty provisions of the contract for failing to attain the design speed because it had specified the machinery to be used. They carried a maximum of {{convert|1050|LT|t}} of coal which allowed them to steam for {{convert|3750|lk=in|nmi}} at a speed of {{convert|10|kn}}.{{sfn|McLaughlin|pp=85, 90}}

=== Armament ===
[[File:Battleship Petropavlosk in completion.jpg|thumb|''Petropavlovsk'' [[fitting out]], 1896]]
The [[Main battery|main armament]] consisted of two pairs of 40-[[caliber (artillery)|caliber]] [[Russian 12 inch 40 caliber naval gun|12-inch]] guns mounted in French-style center-pivot twin-gun turrets fore and aft. They used hydraulic power for loading and traversing, but the ammunition hoists were electrically powered. They were designed to fire one shell every 90 seconds, but the rate of fire in service proved to be one [[Cartridge (firearms)|round]] every three minutes. The structure of the turrets proved to be too weak to withstand extra-strength charges and had to be reinforced. These guns had a maximum elevation of 15° and could traverse 270°. 58 rounds per gun were carried.{{sfn|McLaughlin|pp=84, 87–89}} They fired a {{convert|731.3|lb|kg|adj=on}} shell at a [[muzzle velocity]] of {{convert|2598|ft/s|m/s|abbr=on}} to a range of {{convert|12010|yd|m}} at an elevation of 10°.{{sfn|NavWeaps (12"/40)}}

The secondary armament of the ships consisted of a dozen 45-caliber [[Canet guns|Canet]] Model 1892 six-inch quick-firing (QF) guns, eight mounted in four twin-gun turrets on the upper deck and four pedestal-mounted guns in [[embrasure]]s on the sides of the hull, one deck below and between the turrets. The turrets were traversed by and the ammunition hoists were worked by electric motors, but the guns were elevated manually. They had an 135° arc of fire and the guns could elevate to a maximum of +15° and depress to −5°. The rate of fire of the turret-mounted guns was generally only about half that (2–3 [[Cartridge (firearms)|rounds]] per minute) of the pedestal-mounted guns. The motors and mechanism of the ammunition hoists were problematic and sometimes reduced the rate of fire down of one round per minute. The guns in the hull could traverse 100° and each six-inch gun was provided with 200 rounds.{{sfn|McLaughlin|pp=84, 89}} They fired shells that weighed {{convert|91.27|lb|kg|abbr=on}} with a muzzle velocity of {{convert|2600|ft/s|m/s|abbr=on}}. They had a maximum range of {{convert|12600|yd|m}} when fired at an elevation of +20°.{{sfn|NavWeaps (6"/45)}}

A number of smaller guns were carried for defense against [[torpedo boat]]s. These included twelve{{refn|group=Note|''Sevastopol'' carried only ten 47-millimeter guns. {{harvnb|McLaughlin|pp=84, 89}}.}} {{convert|47|mm|adj=on|sp=us}} [[Hotchkiss gun]]s in hull embrasures and on the superstructure.{{sfn|McLaughlin|pp=84, 89}} They fired a {{convert|3.3|lb|kg|adj=on}} shell at a muzzle velocity of {{convert|1476|ft/s|m/s|abbr=on}} at a rate of 20 rounds per minute to a range of {{convert|2020|yd|m}}.{{sfn|NavWeaps (47 mm/5)}} Twenty smaller {{convert|37|mm|adj=on|sp=us}} Hotchkiss guns were positioned in hull embrasures, on the superstructure and in the [[Top (sailing ship)|fighting tops]].{{sfn|McLaughlin|pp=84, 89}} They fired a {{convert|1.1|lb|kg|adj=on}} shell at a muzzle velocity of {{convert|1450|ft/s|m/s|abbr=on}}. They had a rate of fire of 20 rounds per minute and a maximum range of {{convert|3038|yd|m}}.{{sfn|NavWeaps (37 mm/5)}}

The ''Petropavlovsk''-class ships carried four {{convert|15|in|mm|0|adj=on}} [[torpedo tube]]s, all above water, mounted on the [[broadside]] and two broadside {{convert|18|in|mm|0|adj=on}} underwater tubes. The forward 15-inch tubes were near the forward main gun turret and were unprotected by any armor; aft, the 15-inch tubes were protected by the upper armor belt. The underwater tubes were protected underneath the armor [[deck (ship)|deck]], forward of the forward 12-inch [[magazine (artillery)|magazine]].{{sfn|McLaughlin|pp=84, 89}} The 15-inch Type L torpedo carried a {{convert|141|lb|adj=on}} [[warhead]] of [[Trinitrotoluene|TNT]]. It had two speed settings which gave it a maximum range of {{convert|980|yd}} at {{convert|25|kn}} or {{convert|660|yd}} at {{convert|29|kn}}. No data is available for the 18-inch torpedo.{{sfn|NavWeaps (Torpedoes)}} The ship also carried 50 [[Naval mine|mines]] to be laid to protect her anchorage in remote areas.{{sfn|McLaughlin|p=89}}

The ships were fitted with Liuzhol [[Stadiametric rangefinding|stadiametric rangefinders]] that used the angle between two vertical points on an enemy ship, usually the waterline and the [[crow's nest]], to estimate the range. The gunnery officer consulted his references to get the range and calculated the proper elevation and [[deflection (ballistics)|deflection]] required to hit the target. He transmitted his commands via a Geisler electro-mechanical [[Fire-control system#Naval fire control|fire-control transmission system]] to each gun or turret.{{sfn|Forczyk|pp=27–28, 57}}

=== Protection ===
The Russian armor plate industry had not yet mastered the process for forming thick steel plates so the armor for these ships was ordered from companies in Germany and the United States. Even they could not produce enough of the latest types of armor plate in the quantities required for all three ships. ''Petropavlovsk'' had ordinary nickel steel, while ''Sevastopol'' used [[Harvey armor]] and ''Poltava'' used the latest [[Krupp armor]]. The thicknesses of the armor plates varied in an attempt to equalize their effectiveness. In ''Petropavlovsk'', the maximum thickness of the waterline armor belt over the machinery spaces was {{convert|16|in|mm|0}} which reduced to {{convert|12|in|mm|0}} abreast the [[magazine (artillery)|magazine]]s. The belt tapered to a thickness of {{convert|8|in|mm|0}} at its bottom edge. The belt armor in the other two ships was {{convert|14.5|in|mm|0}} over the machinery spaces and thinned to {{convert|10|in|mm|0}} over the magazines. Their belt tapered to a thickness of {{convert|7.25|in|mm|0}} at its lower edge. The belt covered {{convert|240|ft|m|1}} of the ship's length and was {{convert|7|ft|6|in|1}} high, of which the upper {{convert|36|in|1}} was intended to be above the waterline. The belt terminated in a transverse [[bulkhead (partition)|bulkhead]] {{convert|9|in|mm|0}} thick forward and eight inches thick aft, leaving the ends of the ships unprotected. Above the waterline belt was an upper [[strake]] of {{convert|5|in|mm|0|adj=on}} armor that ran between the turret bases, seven and a half feet high. The ends of the upper belt were closed off by five-inch angled transverse bulkheads that connected the ends of the upper belt to the turret support tubes.{{sfn|McLaughlin|p=89}}

The armor of the main gun turrets and their supporting tubes was ten inches thick (Krupp armor in ''Poltava'', nickel steel in the other two) with roofs {{convert|2|in|mm|0}} thick. The turrets of the secondary armament had five-inch sides with {{convert|1|in|mm|0}} roofs. The six-inch guns in the hull embrasures were unprotected. The sides of the [[conning tower]] were nine inches thick while the armor deck in the central citadel was two inches thick. Outside the area covered by the belt armor, the flat portion of the deck was {{convert|2.5|in|mm|0}} thick, while the sloped portion was {{convert|3|in|mm|0}} thick.{{sfn|McLaughlin|p=90}}

